# Documented gitleaks false-positives. Each entry is a per-commit
# fingerprint of the form `<sha>:<path>:<rule>:<line>`. The regex
# wins when a documentation example happens to look like a secret;
# we keep the example for operator-facing docs and acknowledge the
# false positive here.
#
# Doctrine D18 is preserved: every entry is a NON-SECRET (a
# documentation reference, a public spec fragment, an algorithm
# identifier). A real secret would be rotated and removed, never
# allow-listed.
#
# Format: <commit-sha>:<path>:<rule-id>:<line>
# Adding entries: paste the `Fingerprint:` line from
# `gitleaks detect -v` output, one per line.

# docs/security/post-quantum-agility.md line 123 — documents the
# expected `Server Temp Key: X25519MLKEM768` output from
# `openssl s_client`; the openssl-style key-value pair trips the
# generic-api-key rule. The string is a public TLS-1.3
# algorithm identifier, not a secret. Fix landed at HEAD (the text
# is rephrased to not match the regex), but historical commits in
# this PR's range still carry the original — the ignore lets the
# PR's gitleaks gate pass.
